<SCHEMA-FIELD-GUIDANCE>
- module: Logical module name (e.g. folder or file group). If not derivable, use "__UNSET__".
- constants: ONLY literal domain constants directly used for logic (IDs, thresholds, mapping objects). Omit infrastructure/env constants (URLs, ports). Scalar or object constants defined in source.
  - name: Identifier as it appears.
  - value: Literal value snippet (stringified if object) truncated if extremely large; do NOT invent hidden values.
  - description: Natural-language description of its domain purpose (if evident); else "__UNSET__".
- functions: Each business-logic function.
  - rules: High-level domain rule statements distilled from the function without adding new semantics. Each should trace to one or more lines.
  - decision_points: Individual condition evaluations (if/else, switch case, ternary). condition: textual expression. outcome: resulting action (e.g. "return []", "set movementType=ARRIVAL", "throw 'invalid age'").
  - mappings: Explicit mapping operations (lookups, enumerations, dictionary access). source: origin identifier/expression; target: resulting value; description: purpose.
  - transformations: Data shape changes (object construction, field derivation, normalization like trimming, replacing spaces).
  - filters: Predicate statements used to exclude items or short-circuit returns.
  - calculations: Deterministic numeric/time computations, including intermediate variable calculations.
  - constants_used: Names of constants referenced directly.
EMPTY COLLECTIONS: Use [] (not ["__UNSET__"]). For any scalar field missing, use "__UNSET__".
</SCHEMA-FIELD-GUIDANCE>

